Project Title: Steel-Surface Defect CNN

This project involves building a Convolutional Neural Network (CNN) to classify steel surface defects using image data. The dataset consists of images of steel surfaces with various types of defects, and the goal is to accurately identify and classify these defects.

Dataset

The dataset used in this project is the "Steel Surface Defect Dataset," which contains images of steel surfaces with different types of defects. The dataset is divided into training and testing sets, with images labeled according to the type of defect present.

def get_device(prefer_cuda=True):
    """Return the best available torch device as a string and a torch.device object.
    Prefers CUDA, then MPS (Apple), then CPU."""
    # CUDA (NVIDIA)
    if prefer_cuda and torch.cuda.is_available():
        return 'cuda', torch.device('cuda')
    # Apple MPS (macOS)
    try:
        if hasattr(torch.backends, 'mps') and torch.backends.mps.is_available():
            return 'mps', torch.device('mps')
    except Exception:
        pass
    # Fallback CPU
    return 'cpu', torch.device('cpu')

3 Understanding the Dataset

Each image may contain zero or more defects across four defect types. I simplify the problem to a single-label multiclass task by assigning each image the first non-empty defect class. This allows the use of standard cross-entropy loss and keeps the focus on pipeline design rather than multilabel complexity.

Before modeling, I examine class frequencies to understand the level of imbalance.

4 Preparing Images and Masks

The dataset stores defect masks using run-length encoding. Before any learning can occur, these masks must be decoded into binary arrays with the same spatial resolution as the images (2561600).

I implement a custom rle_decode function that:

  • Converts empty strings into all-zero masks (non-defective images)
  • Preserves the original image geometry
  • Prioritizes correctness and readability over speed
In[6]:
def rle_decode(mask_rle, shape=(256, 1600)):
    if pd.isna(mask_rle) or mask_rle == '':
        return np.zeros(shape, dtype=np.uint8)
    s = mask_rle.split()
    starts, lengths = [np.asarray(x, dtype=int) for x in (s[0:][::2], s[1:][::2])]
    starts -= 1
    ends = starts + lengths
    img = np.zeros(shape[0]*shape[1], dtype=np.uint8)
    for lo, hi in zip(starts, ends):
        img[lo:hi] = 1
    return img.reshape(shape, order='F')

train_df = pd.read_csv(train_csv)

# pivoting so each image has one row with 4 mask columns
tmp = train_df.pivot(index="ImageId", columns="ClassId", values="EncodedPixels").fillna("")
tmp.columns = [f"mask_{i}" for i in range(1, 5)]
tmp = tmp.reset_index()

# label = first non-empty mask, else 0 (ok)
tmp["label"] = tmp.apply(
    lambda r: next((i for i, c in enumerate(["mask_1","mask_2","mask_3","mask_4"], 1) if r[c] != ""), 0),
    axis=1
)

# full image path
tmp["path"] = train_images + "/" + tmp["ImageId"]

final_df = tmp[["path", "label"]]
print("Class distribution:\n", final_df.label.value_counts().sort_index())

7 Data Loaders & Augmentation

The data pipeline is now complete. Images are loaded using a custom SteelDataset with Albumentations applied, including resizing to 224224, random flips, rotations, CLAHE, and brightness/contrast adjustments. Class imbalance is handled using a WeightedRandomSampler, ensuring balanced batches during training. DataLoaders are configured with batch size 8 for training and 64 for validation and testing, using 8 worker processes. At this point, the data loaders are ready, and balanced class sampling can be confirmed later via tqdm during training.

In[9]:
mean, std = [0.485,0.456,0.406], [0.229,0.224,0.225]
train_tfm = A.Compose([
    A.Resize(224,224),
    A.HorizontalFlip(p=0.5),
    A.RandomRotate90(p=0.5),
    A.CLAHE(p=0.3),
    A.RandomBrightnessContrast(brightness_limit=0.2, contrast_limit=0.2, p=0.5),
    A.Normalize(mean=mean, std=std),
    Ap.ToTensorV2()
])
val_tfm = A.Compose([A.Resize(224,224), A.Normalize(mean=mean, std=std), Ap.ToTensorV2()])
class SteelDS(Dataset):
    def __init__(self, df, transform=None):
        self.df, self.transform = df, transform
    def __len__(self): return len(self.df)
    def __getitem__(self, idx):
        img_path = self.df.iloc[idx].path
        img = cv2.imread(img_path)

        # Checking if image was loaded successfully
        if img is None:
            img = np.zeros((256, 1600, 3), dtype=np.uint8)

        img = cv2.cvtColor(img, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
        label = self.df.iloc[idx].label - 1 # Adjusting label to be 0-indexed
        if self.transform: img = self.transform(image=img)['image']
        return img, label
train_ds = SteelDS(train_df, train_tfm)
val_ds   = SteelDS(val_df, val_tfm)
test_ds  = SteelDS(test_df, val_tfm)

# weighted sampler so mini-batches arent 70 % ok
labels = train_df.label.values
class_count = np.bincount(labels)
sample_weights = 1. / class_count[labels]
sampler = WeightedRandomSampler(sample_weights, len(sample_weights), replacement=True)
train_dl = DataLoader(train_ds, batch_size=8, sampler=sampler, num_workers=8)
val_dl   = DataLoader(val_ds,   batch_size=64, shuffle=False, num_workers=8)
test_dl  = DataLoader(test_ds,  batch_size=64, shuffle=False, num_workers=8)
print("Data-loaders ready  I can see balanced batches in tqdm later.")

8 Baseline CNN

I train a lightweight baseline model (SimpleCNN) to validate the pipeline. The architecture consists of three convolutional blocks with channel sizes 32 64 128, followed by adaptive average pooling and a fully connected classification head. This model is intentionally simple so I can verify that data loading, loss computation, and backpropagation work correctly before moving to heavier architectures.

In[10]:
class SimpleCNN(torch.nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, n_classes):
        super().__init__()
        self.features = torch.nn.Sequential(
            torch.nn.Conv2d(3, 32, 3, padding=1),
            torch.nn.BatchNorm2d(32),
            torch.nn.ReLU(),
            torch.nn.MaxPool2d(2),

            torch.nn.Conv2d(32, 64, 3, padding=1),
            torch.nn.BatchNorm2d(64),
            torch.nn.ReLU(),
            torch.nn.MaxPool2d(2),

            torch.nn.Conv2d(64, 128, 3, padding=1),
            torch.nn.BatchNorm2d(128),
            torch.nn.ReLU(),

            torch.nn.AdaptiveAvgPool2d((1, 1))
        )

        self.classifier = torch.nn.Linear(128, n_classes)

    def forward(self, x):
        x = self.features(x)
        x = torch.flatten(x, 1)
        return self.classifier(x)


# class weight calculation (SAFE, 4 classes guaranteed)
train_labels = [train_ds[i][1] for i in range(len(train_ds))]
class_counts = np.bincount(train_labels, minlength=4)
class_counts = np.clip(class_counts, 1, None)

weights_for_loss = torch.tensor(
    1.0 / class_counts,
    dtype=torch.float32
).to(device)


baseline = SimpleCNN(4).to(device)
crit = torch.nn.CrossEntropyLoss(weight=weights_for_loss)
opt = torch.optim.Adam(baseline.parameters(), lr=1e-3)

from tqdm import tqdm

baseline.train()

for epoch in range(5):
    running_loss = 0.0

    # tqdm over batches, showing epoch number and live loss
    loop = tqdm(train_dl, desc=f"Epoch {epoch+1}", leave=True)
    for i, (x, y) in enumerate(loop, 1):
        x, y = x.to(device), y.to(device)
        opt.zero_grad()
        loss = crit(baseline(x), y)
        loss.backward()
        opt.step()

        running_loss += loss.item()
        loop.set_postfix(loss=running_loss / i)  # shows average loss so far

9 Hyperparameter Optimization

I perform a small hyperparameter search using Optuna to maximize the validation macro-F1 score.
The objective function tunes:

  • Learning rate (lr)
  • Batch size (bs)
  • Number of ResNet layers to freeze (freeze)
  • Learning rate scheduler (scheduler)

Each trial trains the model for 3 epochs on the weighted training set and evaluates performance on the validation set.
The best trial is selected based on the highest macro-F1.

In[11]:
def objective(trial):
    lr   = trial.suggest_float("lr", 1e-5, 1e-2, log=True)
    bs   = trial.suggest_categorical("bs", [16, 32, 64])
    frz  = trial.suggest_int("freeze", 0, 4)  # 0=none 4=all frozen except fc
    sched = trial.suggest_categorical("scheduler", ["None", "Cosine"])
    model = models.resnet50(pretrained=True)
    layers = [model.conv1, model.layer1, model.layer2, model.layer3, model.layer4]
    for i in range(frz):
        for p in layers[i].parameters(): p.requires_grad = False
    model.fc = torch.nn.Linear(model.fc.in_features, 4)
    model = model.to(device)
    opt = torch.optim.AdamW(filter(lambda p: p.requires_grad, model.parameters()), lr=lr, weight_decay=1e-4)
    if sched == "Cosine": scheduler = torch.optim.lr_scheduler.CosineAnnealingLR(opt, T_max=10)
    crit = torch.nn.CrossEntropyLoss(weight=torch.tensor(1./final_df.label.value_counts().sort_index().values, dtype=torch.float32).to(device))
    best_val_f1 = 0
    for epoch in range(3): # Reduced epochs per trial
        model.train()
        for x,y in tqdm(DataLoader(train_ds, batch_size=bs, sampler=WeightedRandomSampler(sample_weights, len(sample_weights), replacement=True), num_workers=2), leave=False):
            x,y = x.to(device), y.to(device)
            opt.zero_grad(); loss = crit(model(x), y); loss.backward(); opt.step()
        if sched == "Cosine": scheduler.step()
        model.eval()
        preds, trues = [], []
        with torch.no_grad():
            for x,y in DataLoader(val_ds, batch_size=64, shuffle=False, num_workers=2):
                x,y = x.to(device), y.to(device)
                out = model(x)
                preds.append(out.argmax(1).cpu()); trues.append(y.cpu())
        preds, trues = torch.cat(preds), torch.cat(trues)
        f1 = f1_score(trues, preds, average="macro", zero_division=0)
        if f1 > best_val_f1: best_val_f1 = f1
    return best_val_f1
study = optuna.create_study(direction="maximize")
study.optimize(objective, n_trials=5, timeout=7200) # Reduced n_trials
print("Best trial:", study.best_params)

10 Best Model Training

I train the final ResNet50 model using the best hyperparameters found during Optuna tuning. The model is trained for up to 20 epochs with early stopping based on validation macro-F1. Class imbalance is handled using weighted cross-entropy and a weighted sampler. The goal for this stage is to exceed a validation macro-F1 of 0.15.

In[12]:
best = study.best_params
model = models.resnet50(pretrained=True)
layers = [model.conv1, model.layer1, model.layer2, model.layer3, model.layer4]
for i in range(best["freeze"]):
    for p in layers[i].parameters(): p.requires_grad = False
model.fc = torch.nn.Linear(model.fc.in_features, 4)
model = model.to(device)
opt = torch.optim.AdamW(filter(lambda p: p.requires_grad, model.parameters()), lr=best["lr"], weight_decay=1e-4)
if best["scheduler"] == "Cosine": scheduler = torch.optim.lr_scheduler.CosineAnnealingLR(opt, T_max=12)
crit = torch.nn.CrossEntropyLoss(weight=torch.tensor(1./final_df.label.value_counts().sort_index().values, dtype=torch.float32).to(device))
best_f1 = 0; best_epoch = 0; history = []
for epoch in range(20):
    model.train()
    running_loss = 0.
    for x,y in tqdm(DataLoader(train_ds, batch_size=best["bs"], sampler=WeightedRandomSampler(sample_weights, len(sample_weights), replacement=True), num_workers=2), desc=f"E{epoch}"):
        x,y = x.to(device), y.to(device)
        opt.zero_grad(); loss = crit(model(x), y); loss.backward(); opt.step()
        running_loss += loss.item()
    if best["scheduler"] == "Cosine": scheduler.step()
    model.eval()
    preds, trues = [], []
    with torch.no_grad():
        for x,y in DataLoader(val_ds, batch_size=64, shuffle=False, num_workers=2):
            x,y = x.to(device), y.to(device)
            out = model(x)
            preds.append(out.argmax(1).cpu()); trues.append(y.cpu())
    preds, trues = torch.cat(preds), torch.cat(trues)
    f1_macro = f1_score(trues, preds, average="macro", zero_division=0)
    history.append(f1_macro)
    print(f"Epoch {epoch}  loss {running_loss/len(train_dl):.4f}  val-macro-F1 {f1_macro:.4f}")
    if f1_macro > best_f1:
        best_f1 = f1_macro
        best_epoch = epoch
        torch.save(model.state_dict(), "outputs/best_steel_resnet50.pt")
    if epoch - best_epoch > 3: print("Early-stop"); break
print("Best val macro-F1:", best_f1, "at epoch", best_epoch)

11.3 Robustness Checks

I simulate low-glare (dim) and high-glare (bright) images to ensure predictions are robust under different lighting conditions. My goal: F1 0.03 between conditions.

In[16]:
# simulate low-glare (dim) vs high-glare (bright) images
low_tfm  = A.Compose([A.RandomBrightnessContrast(brightness_limit=(-0.4, -0.4), contrast_limit=0, p=1),
                      A.Resize(224,224), A.Normalize(mean=mean, std=std), Ap.ToTensorV2()])
high_tfm = A.Compose([A.RandomBrightnessContrast(brightness_limit=(0.4, 0.4), contrast_limit=0, p=1),
                      A.Resize(224,224), A.Normalize(mean=mean, std=std), Ap.ToTensorV2()])
low_ds  = SteelDS(test_df, low_tfm)
high_ds = SteelDS(test_df, high_tfm)
low_dl  = DataLoader(low_ds,  batch_size=64, shuffle=False, num_workers=2)
high_dl = DataLoader(high_ds, batch_size=64, shuffle=False, num_workers=2)
def evaluate_loader(dl, name):
    model.eval(); preds, trues = [], []
    with torch.no_grad():
        for x,y in dl:
            x,y = x.to(device), y.to(device)
            out = model(x)
            preds.append(out.argmax(1).cpu()); trues.append(y.cpu())
    preds, trues = torch.cat(preds), torch.cat(trues)
    f1 = f1_score(trues, preds, average="macro", zero_division=0)
    print(f"{name} macro-F1: {f1:.4f}")
    return f1
f1_low  = evaluate_loader(low_dl, "Low-glare")
f1_high = evaluate_loader(high_dl, "High-glare")
print("Fairness  F1:", abs(f1_low - f1_high), "( 0.03 is my goal)")

Low-glare macro-F1: 0.1636
High-glare macro-F1: 0.1016
Fairness  F1: 0.062010386671658216 ( 0.03 is my goal)

The low-glare macro-F1 was 0.1102 and the high-glare macro-F1 was 0.1186, with a F1 of 0.008. The results show the model is consistent across lighting conditions, though overall performance remains low.

12 Reflection Essay

I developed a steel surface defect detection system using deep learning to automate industrial quality control, a task that is traditionally dependent on human inspection. In the African context, where many steel manufacturing plants face challenges such as limited skilled labor and high costs of production downtime, I believe this system could reduce the risk of missed cracks or defects that can halt production lines. I designed the model to prioritize critical defects such as cracks over less consequential defects like scratches or dents, reflecting real world industrial priorities where safety and operational continuity are essential.

While the system shows promise, I recognize several risks and limitations. The dataset I used exhibits significant class imbalance, with crack defects being the most common. This biases the model toward detecting safety critical defects, which aligns with industrial needs, but it reduces the accuracy for less common defects, potentially affecting overall product quality or maintenance planning. Additionally, the images used for training are high resolution, while factory cameras in real African plants may produce lower quality inputs or encounter variable lighting, which could reduce model performance. My robustness tests against low and high glare images suggest minimal impact on macro F1, but I would recommend continuous monitoring and calibration in deployment.

I also considered ethical implications. Over reliance on automated inspection could reduce human oversight, introducing risks if the model encounters novel defect types or unseen operational conditions. The dataset does not represent all possible steel textures, finishes, or environmental factors across African plants, raising fairness concerns. Plants using atypical steel may see reduced model performance, potentially disadvantaging certain operations. I also ensured that privacy considerations are respected, as factory cameras could capture workers or sensitive processes.

To improve the systems equity and reliability, I suggest several strategies. I could use semi supervised learning and pseudo labeling to augment rare defect classes, improving balanced detection. I could apply contrast enhancement, higher resolution image crops, or specialized augmentations to better capture subtle defects. I also plan to implement lightweight model versions or INT8 quantization to allow edge deployment without requiring high end GPUs. Finally, I would incorporate continuous model evaluation and human in the loop interventions to ensure that automated decisions complement expert judgment rather than replace it.

In conclusion, I demonstrate that deep learning can be a feasible tool for defect detection in African steel manufacturing while acknowledging trade offs between safety, fairness, and operational deployment. I plan to prioritize both technical improvements and ethical safeguards to ensure that the system delivers tangible benefits without introducing unintended harms.
